</table>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>The sampled signal consists of impulses spaced every <em>T</em> seconds. The <em>n</em><sup><em>th</em></sup> impulse, located at <em>t = nT</em>, has a strength <em>x(nT),</em> the value of<em> x(t) </em>at <em>t = nT</em>, </big><span lang="EN-US"> </span><span lang="EN-US"> </span><span lang="EN-US"> </span><span lang="EN-US"> </span><span lang="EN-US"> </span></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <big>&nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=f34250ea1b19d490979a4b7e09e55629.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»§apos;«/mo»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«msub»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«/msub»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«munder»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«/munder»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" title="Double click to edit" align="middle">..............(1)</big></p>
<p><big>Since the impulse train <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=0348533665828f2060795dc755d2f5fb.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«/msub»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" align="middle">is a periodic signal of period <em>T</em>, it can be expressed as a trigonometric Fourier series</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<big> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=592a0a66336fbc6c424193a5653c2930.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«/msub»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mfrac»«mn»1«/mn»«mi»T«/mi»«/mfrac»«mo»[«/mo»«mn»1«/mn»«mo»+«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»cos«/mi»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»+«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»cos«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»+«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»cos«/mi»«mn»3«/mn»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»+«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo»]«/mo»«/math»" align="middle">................(2) &nbsp;</big></p>
<p><big>&nbsp;where &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=730590302143e3241e5f339e854b3584.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mo»=«/mo»«mfrac»«mrow»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«/mrow»«mi»T«/mi»«/mfrac»«mo»=«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«/math»" align="middle"> &nbsp; &nbsp;</big></p>
<p><big>Therefore &nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=a781ada213f5a31f2ce0e00a42f7204e.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»§apos;«/mo»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«msub»«mi»§#948;«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«/msub»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mfrac»«mn»1«/mn»«mi»T«/mi»«/mfrac»«mo»[«/mo»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»+«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»cos«/mi»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»+«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»cos«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»+«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»cos«/mi»«mn»3«/mn»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»+«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo».«/mo»«mo»]«/mo»«/math»" title="Double click to edit" align="middle">&nbsp; .........(3)</big></p>
<p><big>To find <em>X<sup>&#039;</sup>(f)</em>, the Fourier transform of<em> x&#039;(t)</em>, we take the Fourier transform of the right hand side of the above equation, term by term. The transform of the first term in the bracket of the above equation (3) is <em>X(f)</em>. Similarly the transform of the second term<img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=c97925c719470aca099bcfdd992bbf81.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»cos«/mi»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" align="middle">is<img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=0ea812845014cb1aa9566e99839c589c.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»X«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»+«/mo»«mi»X«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»+«/mo»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" align="middle">. This represents spectrum <em>X(f)</em> shifted to<img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=88488340e967bc427225f26078ee1c56.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle">and<img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=4f4565a047502fe4f32108a274088f94.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mo»-«/mo»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle">and so on to infinity. This result means that the spectrum <em>X<sup>&#039;</sup>(f)</em> consists of <em>X(f)</em> repeating periodically with period<img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=9be383fea0456fbc3817863dcfbc3e6b.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mo»=«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«mo»/«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle">rad/s, or <em>f</em><sub><em>s</em></sub> =1/T Hz, as shown in Fig.4.  Therefore</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<big> <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=eb4437a7fbe863a89ea5942538eaae5d.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»X«/mi»«mo»§apos;«/mo»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mfrac»«mn»1«/mn»«mi»T«/mi»«/mfrac»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/munderover»«mi»X«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«msub»«mi»§#969;«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" align="middle"></big></p>
<p><big>If we want to reconstruct <em>x(t)</em> from <em>x&#039;(t)</em>, we should be able to recover <em>X(f)</em>&nbsp; from <em>X<sup>&#039;</sup>(f)</em>. This recovery is possible if there is no overlap between successive cycles of <em>X<sup>&#039;</sup>(f)</em>. From Fig.4 we noted that for no overlap between successive cycle of <em>X<sup>&#039;</sup>(f)</em> we should have</big></p>
<p><big>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=f966e3ee6a82d4bc09970fb55856697b.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mo»§#10878;«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»D«/mi»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle">&nbsp; or&nbsp; </em></big><big><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=d92ce9e510ae74eaf2e3fdf21f722dfa.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»§#10877;«/mo»«mn»1«/mn»«mo»/«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»D«/mi»«/math»" align="middle"></big></p>
<p><big>Thus as long as the sampling frequency <em>f</em><sub><em>s</em></sub> is greater than twice the signal bandwidth <em>D </em>(in Hz), <em>X<sup>&#039;</sup>(f)</em> will consist of nonoverlapping repetitions of <em>X(f)</em>. In such a case it indicates that <em>x(t)</em> can be recovered from its samples <em>x&#039;(t)</em> by passing the sampled signal <em>x&#039;(t)</em> through an ideal low pass filter of bandwidth <em>D</em> Hz. If a signal is sampled with a sampling frequency <em>f<sub>s</sub></em> which is below the highest frequency present in the signal then </big><big>the signal </big><big>is called <strong>under</strong><strong>sampled</strong> signal and if the signal is sampled with a sampling frequency <em>f<sub>s</sub> </em>which is slightly higher than twice the bandwidth of the signal or highest frequency present in the signal then the signal is called <strong>over</strong><strong>sampled</strong> signal.<br>
</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;   &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/index.php?sub=59&amp;brch=166&amp;sim=820&amp;cnt=1#link6"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><blink>Top</blink></big></span><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/images/smiley/msn/thumbs_up.gif" alt="" align="absMiddle"></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="link4"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Aliasing:</strong></big></span></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>In reconstructing a signal from its samples, there is another   practical difficulty. The sampling theorem was proved on the assumption   that the signal <em>x(t)</em> is bandlimited. All practical signals are   time limited, i.e., they are of finite duration. As a signal cannot   be timelimited and bandlimited simultaneously. Thus, if a signal is   timelimited, it cannot be bandlimited and vice versa (but it can be   simultaneously non timelimited and non bandlimited). Clearly it can be said that   all practical signals which are necessaily timelimited, are non   bandlimited, they have infinite bandwidth and the spectrum <em>X<sup>&#039;</sup>(f)</em> consists of overlapping cycles of <em>X(f)</em> repeating every <em>f</em><sub><em>s</em></sub> Hz (sampling frequency). Because of infinite bandwidth, the spectral   overlap will always be present regardless of what ever may be the sampling rate chosen.   Because of the overlapping tails, <em>X<sup>&#039;</sup>(f)</em> has not complete information about <em>X(f)</em> and it is not possible, even theoretically to recover <em>x(t)</em> from the sampled signal <em>x&#039;(t)</em>. If the sampled signal is passed through an ideal lowpass filter, the output is not <em>X(f)</em> but a version of <em>X(f)</em> distorted as a result of some causes:</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
    <li>
    <p><big>The loss of the tail of <em>X(f)</em> beyond<em> |</em><em>f | &gt; f<sub>s</sub>/2</em>&nbsp; Hz.</big></p>
    </li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ul>
    <li>
    <p><big>The reappearance of this tail inverted or folded onto the spectrum. The spectra cross at frequency <em>f<sub>s</sub>/2 = 1/2T&nbsp;</em> Hz. This frequency is called the <strong>folding frequency</strong>. The spectrum folds   onto itself at the folding frequency. For instance, a component of   frequency </big><em><big>(f<sub>s</sub></big><big>/2)+ f<sub>x</sub></big></em><big> shows up as or act like a component of lower frequency <em>(f<sub>s</sub>/2)- f<sub>x </sub></em>in the reconstructed signal. Thus the components of frequencies above <em>f<sub>s</sub>/2</em> reappear as components of frequencies below <em>f<sub>s</sub>/2</em>. This tail inversion is known as <strong>spectral folding</strong> or <strong>aliasing </strong>which is shown in Fig. 5. In this process of aliasing not only we are losing all the components of frequencies above <em>f<sub>s</sub>/2</em> Hz, but these very components reappear as lower frequency components.   This reappearance destroys the integrity of the lower frequency   components.</big></p>
    </li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" width="200">
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><img src="/userfiles/7/image/sig6/sig8/aliasd.jpg" alt="" align="absMiddle" height="143" width="270"></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <big>Fig.5&nbsp; Aliased signal</big></td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/index.php?sub=59&amp;brch=166&amp;sim=820&amp;cnt=1#link2"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><blink>Top</blink></big></span><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/images/smiley/msn/thumbs_up.gif" alt="" align="absMiddle"></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="link5"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Sampling of Non-bandlimited Signal: Anti-aliasing Filter</strong></big></span></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>Anti aliasing filter is a filter which is used before a signal   sampler, to restrict the bandwidth of a signal to approximately satisfy   the sampling theorem. The potential defectors are all the frequency components beyond <em>f<sub>s</sub>/2</em> Hz. We should have to eliminate these components from <em>x(t)</em> before sampling <em>x(t)</em>. As a result of this we lose only the components beyond the folding frequency <em>f<sub>s</sub>/2</em> Hz. These frequency components cannot reappear to corrupt the components with frequencies below the folding frequency. This suppression of higher frequencies can be   accomplished by an ideal filter of bandwidth <em>f<sub>s</sub>/2</em> Hz. This filter is called the<strong> anti-aliasing filter</strong>.   The anti aliasing operation must be performed before the signal is   sampled. The anti aliasing filter, being an ideal filter is   unrealizable. In practice, we use a steep cutoff filter, which leaves a   sharply attenuated residual spectrum beyond the folding frequency <em>f<sub>s</sub>/2</em>.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="link3">&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Signal Reconstruction:</strong></big></span></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>The process of reconstructing a continuous time signal <em>x(t)</em> from its samples is known as <strong>interpolation</strong>. In the sampling theorem we saw that a signal <em>x(t)</em> band limited to<em> D</em> Hz can be reconstructed from its samples. This reconstruction is   accomplished by passing the sampled signal through an ideal low pass   filter of bandwidth <em>D</em> Hz. As seen in the above equation(3), the sampled signal contains a component <img title="Double click to edit" class="Wirisformula" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mo»(«/mo»«mn»1«/mn»«mo»/«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=56c09e305c7883f301e8516491a00ff3.png" align="middle">and to recover <em>x(t) </em>or <em>X(f)</em>, the sampled signal must be passed through an ideal lowpass filter having bandwidth <em>D</em> Hz and gain <em>T.</em></big></p>
<p><big>The description of the process of reconstruction in the   frequency domain is to </big><big>f</big><big>ind the DTFT of the discrete-time signal, change the variable <em>F→f / f<sub>s </sub></em>, multiply by <em>T</em> and find the inverse CTFT. We find the DTFT from the samples using</big><span><br>
</span></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=7bd653ef39b1b5064e4a8b47ec159adc.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»X«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»F«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/munderover»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»[«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»]«/mo»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»j«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«mi»F«/mi»«mi»n«/mi»«/mrow»«/msup»«/math»" align="middle"></p>
<p><big>Here we are using the notations<em> X</em><em>(f)</em> for CTFT and <em>X(F)</em> for DTFT.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" width="200">
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/userfiles/7/image/sig6/sampex3.jpg.pagespeed.ce.lEg4a_akmM.jpg" alt="" align="absMiddle" height="145" width="276"></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fig. 6 DTFT of sinc function</big></td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>For sinc function, the DTFT is illustrated in Fig.6. To isolate the function indexed by <em>k = 0</em>, we can multiply the DTFT by a rectangle function that is wide enough to include the <em>k = 0</em> alias but not wide enough to include any other aliases. So the corner of the rectangle must be at a value of <em>F </em>which is greater than<em> F<sub>m</sub>= f<sub>m</sub>/ f<sub>s</sub></em>, where <em>f<sub>m</sub> </em>is the highest frequency present in the signal<em> x(t)</em> but less than <em>1 - F</em><sub><em>m</em></sub> or more compactly, <em>F<sub>m</sub>&lt; F<sub>c</sub>&lt;1 - F<sub>m</sub></em>. The isolated <em>k = 0</em> replica is then</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=99254b7d61883cdc0af5a18c3ba66591.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mrow»«mi»F«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/mrow»«/msub»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»F«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»rect«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mfrac»«mi»F«/mi»«mrow»«mn»2«/mn»«msub»«mi»F«/mi»«mi»c«/mi»«/msub»«/mrow»«/mfrac»«mo»)«/mo»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/munderover»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»[«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»]«/mo»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»j«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«mi»F«/mi»«mi»n«/mi»«/mrow»«/msup»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"></p>
<p><big>Next we make the change of variable <em>F→ f / f<sub>s</sub> </em>and multiply it by <em>T</em>&nbsp;</big></p>
<p><big>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=614faee40eccfadb8ca15739b74c7571.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»X«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mrow»«mi»F«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/mrow»«/msub»«mo»(«/mo»«mfrac»«mi»f«/mi»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«/mfrac»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»rect«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mo»(«/mo»«mfrac»«mi»f«/mi»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«/mfrac»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»/«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«msub»«mi»F«/mi»«mi»c«/mi»«/msub»«mo»)«/mo»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/munderover»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»[«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»]«/mo»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»j«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»n«/mi»«/msub»«mo»/«/mo»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«/mrow»«/msup»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"><br>
</big></p>
<p><big>Now we have to find out the inverse CTFT, which is</big></p>
<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=23cb44a6fcf03c0b1e62d9263816a30d.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«msup»«mi»F«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mn»1«/mn»«/mrow»«/msup»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»X«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«msubsup»«mo»§#8747;«/mo»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/msubsup»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»rect«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mo»(«/mo»«mfrac»«mi»f«/mi»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«/mfrac»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»/«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«msub»«mi»F«/mi»«mi»c«/mi»«/msub»«mo»)«/mo»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/munderover»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»[«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»]«/mo»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»j«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»n«/mi»«/msub»«mo»/«/mo»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«/mrow»«/msup»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mi»j«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»t«/mi»«/msub»«/mrow»«/msup»«mi»d«/mi»«mi»f«/mi»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"></p>
<p><big>&nbsp;Let <em>F<sub>c</sub> = f<sub>c</sub>/f</em><sub><em>s</em></sub> , then&nbsp;</big></p>
<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=7d1b1a97562b98a65b9b0f5a4198ab6a.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«msubsup»«mo»§#8747;«/mo»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/msubsup»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/munderover»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»[«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»]«/mo»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»rect«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»/«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»c«/mi»«/msub»«mo»)«/mo»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»j«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»/«/mo»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«mo»)«/mo»«/mrow»«/msup»«mi»d«/mi»«mi»f«/mi»«/math»" align="middle"></p>
<p><big>By exchanging the order of integration and summation we can   recognize the integrand as a time shifted inverse CTFT of a frequency   domain rectangle function.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=a43909a60a75a0550770885b969e1a72.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/munderover»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»[«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»]«/mo»«msubsup»«mo»§#8747;«/mo»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/msubsup»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»rect«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mfrac»«mi»f«/mi»«mrow»«mn»2«/mn»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»c«/mi»«/msub»«/mrow»«/mfrac»«mo»)«/mo»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»j«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/mrow»«/msup»«mi»d«/mi»«mi»f«/mi»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"></p>
<p><big>Then <em>x[n] = x(nT)</em>, &nbsp;&nbsp;</big>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=e9cda0fd39dbba350bfbc86c4b0745b2.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mo»(«/mo»«mfrac»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»c«/mi»«/msub»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«/msub»«/mfrac»«mo»)«/mo»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/munderover»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»sinc«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»c«/mi»«/msub»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"></p>
<p><big>The reconstruction process consists of replacing each sample by a   sinc function, centered at the time of the sample and scaled by the   sample value<em> x(nT)</em> times&nbsp;<em>2f<sub>c</sub>/ f<sub>s</sub></em> and adding all the functions so created. Suppose the signal is sampled at exactly Nyquist rate <em>f<sub>s</sub>= 2f<sub>m</sub></em>, Then <em>f<sub>m</sub>= f<sub>s</sub>/2 = f<sub>s</sub>- f<sub>m</sub></em> and </big><em><big>F<sub>m</sub></big><big>= 1/2 = 1- F<sub>m</sub></big></em><big>.</big></p>
<p><big>The requirement&nbsp; <em>F<sub>m</sub>&lt; F<sub>c</sub>&lt; 1- F<sub>m</sub></em> cannot be met, in this case we must allow <em>F<sub>c</sub>= F<sub>m</sub></em>, which means that <em>f<sub>c</sub>= f<sub>m</sub>= f<sub>s</sub>/2</em> This will work till the signals spectrum does not have an impulse at&nbsp;<em> f</em><sub><em>m</em></sub>. (If there is an impulse at <em>f<sub>m</sub> ,</em> it will be aliased in the sampling process). In this limiting case, the interppolation is described by the simpler expression</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=3c3a36a56e42fb2fd69dce462dcff526.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mo»-«/mo»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/mrow»«mo»§#8734;«/mo»«/munderover»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»sinc«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mfrac»«mrow»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/mrow»«mi»T«/mi»«/mfrac»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" align="middle"></p>
<p><big>Interpolation consists of simply of multiplying each sinc   function by its corresponding sample value and then adding all the   scaled and shifted sinc functions as shown in Fig.7 given below.</big></p>
<table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" width="200">
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/userfiles/7/image/sig1/abcd.jpg.pagespeed.ce.oF4k8QxbDB.jpg" alt="" align="absMiddle" height="126" width="329"></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
            <td><big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Fig.7 Weighted sinc function.</big></td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>The interpolated value at any point is the sum of contributions from infinitely many weighted sinc functions.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;   &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <a href="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/index.php?sub=59&amp;brch=166&amp;sim=820&amp;cnt=1#link17"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><blink>Top</blink></big></span><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/images/smiley/msn/thumbs_up.gif" alt="" align="absMiddle"></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="link7">&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Zero-order hold:</strong></big></span></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>There are many techniques that can be used to reconstruct a   signal and the selection of the technique to be used is depends on what   accuracy of reconstruction is required and how oversampled the signal   is. Probably the simplest approximate reconstruction idea is to simply   let the reconstruction always be the value of the most recent sample as   shown in Figure 8.</big></p>
<p><big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </big><img src="/userfiles/7/image/sig6/zoh%281%29.jpg" alt="" align="absMiddle" height="171" width="300">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img alt="" src="/userfiles/7/image/sig2/zohimpS.jpg" align="absMiddle" height="174" width="300"></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <big>Fig.8 Zero order hold signal reconstruction.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </big><big>Fig.9 Impulse response of a Zero order hold.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>It is a simple technique because the samples in the form of numerical codes, can be the input signal to a Digital to Analog   converter, which is clocked to produce a new output signal with every   clock pulse. This technique produces a signal which has a stair step   shape that follows the original signal. This type of signal   reconstruction can be modeled (except for quantization effects) by   passing the impulse sampled signal through a system called a <strong>zero order hold</strong> whose impulse response is</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>
<table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" width="200">
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><img src="/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=f42560a4687e17cc5f0e05decd39e8af.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»h«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mfenced close=¨¨ open=¨{¨»«mtable»«mtr»«mtd»«mn»1«/mn»«mo»,«/mo»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mn»0«/mn»«mo»§lt;«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»§lt;«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«/mtd»«/mtr»«mtr»«mtd»«mn»0«/mn»«mo»,«/mo»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mi»o«/mi»«mi»t«/mi»«mi»h«/mi»«mi»e«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«mi»w«/mi»«mi»i«/mi»«mi»s«/mi»«mi»e«/mi»«/mtd»«/mtr»«/mtable»«/mfenced»«mo»=«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»rect«/mi»«mfenced»«mfrac»«mrow»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»/«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«/mrow»«mi»T«/mi»«/mfrac»«/mfenced»«/math»" class="Wirisformula" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"></td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p><big>which is shown in Figure 9.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/index.php?sub=59&amp;brch=166&amp;sim=820&amp;cnt=1#link18"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><blink>Top</blink></big></span><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/images/smiley/msn/thumbs_up.gif" alt="" align="absMiddle"></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="link8"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>First-order hold:</strong></big></span></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>One popular way of further reducing the effects of the aliases   is to follow the zero order hold with a practical lowpass filter that   smooths out the steps caused by the zero order hold. The zero order hold   causes a delay to the original signal because it is causal.</big></p>
<p><big>Another natural reconstruction idea is to interpolate between   samples with straight lines as shown in Fig.10 below. This is obviously a   better approximation of the original signal but it is a little harder   to implement.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <img alt="" src="/userfiles/7/image/sig6/fohlin%281%29.jpg" align="absMiddle" height="184" width="300">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="/userfiles/7/image/sig2/impls_respn-foh%281%29.jpg" alt="" align="absMiddle" height="185" width="300"></p>
<p>&nbsp;<big>Fig.10 Signal reconstruction by straight-line interpolation.&nbsp;&nbsp; Fig.11 Impulse response of causal first-order hold.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>As shown in above figure the value of the interpolated signal at   any time depends on the value of the previous sample and the value of   the next sample and this is not possible in real time because the value   of the next sample is not known in real time. But if we delay the   reconstructed signal by one sample time T, we can make the   reconstruction process causal and the reconstructed signal   would appear as like the Figure 12.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img alt="" src="/userfiles/7/image/sig2/sig7/foh.jpg" align="absMiddle" height="204" width="300"></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<big> Fig.12 Straight line signal reconstruction delayed by one sample time</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>This interpolation can be accomplished by following the zero   order hold by an identical zero order hold. This means that the impulse   response of such a signal reconstruction filter would be the convolution   of the zero order hold impulse response with itself</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;</p>
<table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1" width="200">
    <tbody>
        <tr>
            <td><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=6118605de54d7babfeea3d7e478c1f10.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»h«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»rect«/mi»«mfenced»«mfrac»«mrow»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»/«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«/mrow»«mi»T«/mi»«/mfrac»«/mfenced»«mo»*«/mo»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»rect«/mi»«mfenced»«mfrac»«mrow»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»/«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«/mrow»«mi»T«/mi»«/mfrac»«/mfenced»«mo»=«/mo»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»tri«/mi»«mfenced»«mfrac»«mrow»«mi»t«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«/mrow»«mi»T«/mi»«/mfrac»«/mfenced»«/math»" align="middle"></td>
        </tr>
    </tbody>
</table>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;</p>
<p><big>This type of filter is called <strong>first order hold</strong>. Its transfer function is<img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=81e875d2ed349dbc9ca5d79a365564d5.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»H«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«msup»«mi mathvariant=¨normal¨»sinc«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«/msup»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«mi»f«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»j«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«mi»f«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«/mrow»«/msup»«/math»" align="middle">. This transfer function is similar to that of a zero order hold but attenuates aliases more because its magnitude diminishes faster with increasing frequency.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/index.php?sub=59&amp;brch=166&amp;sim=820&amp;cnt=1#link9"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><blink>Top</blink></big></span><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/images/smiley/msn/thumbs_up.gif" alt="" align="absMiddle"> <br>
</a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="link10"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>The discrete Fourier transform (DFT):</strong></big></span></a></p>
<p><big>If <em>x(kT)</em> and <em>X(rf<sub>0</sub>)</em> are the <em>k</em><sup><em>th</em></sup> and<em> r<sup>th</sup> </em>samples of <em>x(t)</em> and <em>X(f)</em> respectively, then we can define new variables <em>x</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> and<em> X<sub>r</sub> </em>as</big></p>
<p><big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=e784d5541fd22652731fa4acecfe8ecd.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»=«/mo»«mi»T«/mi»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»k«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«mo»=«/mo»«mfrac»«msub»«mi»T«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«msub»«mi»N«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«/mfrac»«mi»x«/mi»«mo»(«/mo»«mi»k«/mi»«mi»T«/mi»«mo»)«/mo»«/math»" align="middle"></big></p>
<p><big>&nbsp;and&nbsp;&nbsp;<em>X<sub>r</sub> = X(rf<sub>0</sub>)</em> &nbsp; where &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=15e803f1e64d2ee6e03736c2b17d6107.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mo»=«/mo»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«msub»«mi»F«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mo»=«/mo»«mfrac»«mrow»«mn»2«/mn»«mi»§#960;«/mi»«/mrow»«msub»«mi»T«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«/mfrac»«/math»" align="middle"></big></p>
<p><big>We will now see that <em>x</em><sub><em>k</em></sub> and <em>X</em><sub><em>r</em></sub> are related by the following equation</big></p>
<p>&nbsp; <big>DFT, &nbsp;&nbsp;</big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=e1529c584a00eb12e8015a4391a63cf4.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«mo»=«/mo»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»k«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mn»0«/mn»«/mrow»«mrow»«msub»«mi»N«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mo»-«/mo»«mn»1«/mn»«/mrow»«/munderover»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»j«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«msub»«mi»§#937;«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mi»k«/mi»«/mrow»«/msup»«/math»" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"></p>
<p>&nbsp;<big>and&nbsp; IDFT </big>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=f3fcb5c46e2503f48ec3db6515d186ad.png" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»=«/mo»«mfrac»«mn»1«/mn»«msub»«mi»N«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«/mfrac»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»r«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mn»0«/mn»«/mrow»«mrow»«msub»«mi»N«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mo»-«/mo»«mn»1«/mn»«/mrow»«/munderover»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mi»j«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«msub»«mi»§#937;«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mi»k«/mi»«/mrow»«/msup»«/math»" title="Double click to edit" align="middle"></p>
<p><big>Here<em> X</em><sub><em>r</em></sub> is the discrete Fourier transform of <em>&#039;x<sub>k</sub>&#039; </em>and <em>&#039;x</em><sub><em>k</em></sub>&#039; is the IDFT of <em>X<sub>r </sub>.</em> The notation&nbsp;<em> x<sub>k</sub> <strong>⇔</strong> X<sub>r</sub>&nbsp;</em> is also used to indicate that <em>x<sub>k</sub> </em>and <em>X</em><sub><em>r</em></sub> are a DFT&nbsp;pair. Remember that <em>x<sub>k</sub> </em>is <em>T<sub>0</sub>/ N<sub>0</sub></em> times the<em> k</em><sup><em>th</em></sup> sample of <em>x(t) </em>and <em>X</em><sub><em>r</em></sub> is the <em>r<sup>th</sup> </em>sample of <em>X(f)</em>.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="link11">&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Picket fence effect:</strong></big></span></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>The numerical computation method yields only the uniform sample values of<em> X(f)</em> or <em>x(t)</em>. Using this method is like viewing a signal and its spectrum through a "picket fence". The major peaks of <em>X(f)</em> or <em>x(t) </em>could   lie between two samples and may remain hidden, there is a situation   giving a false picture of the reality. Such misleading results can be   avoided by using a sufficiently large <em>&#039;N<sub>0</sub></em>&#039; the no. of samples, which increases the resolution.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/index.php?sub=59&amp;brch=166&amp;sim=820&amp;cnt=1#link14"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><blink>Top</blink></big></span><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/images/smiley/msn/thumbs_up.gif" alt="" align="absMiddle"></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;<a name="link13"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Zero padding:</strong></big></span></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>Observing <em>X</em><sub><em>r</em></sub> is like observing the spectrum <em>X(f) </em>through a "picket-fence". If the frequency sampling interval <em>f<sub>0</sub></em>  is not sufficiently small, we could miss out some significant details    and obtain a misleading picture. To obtain a higher number of samples,    we need to reduce <em>f<sub>0</sub></em>. Because <em>f<sub>0</sub> = 1/T<sub>0</sub></em>, a higher number of samples requires us to increase the value of <em>&#039;T<sub>0</sub>&#039; </em>the period of repetition for <em>x(t)</em>. This option increases <em>&#039;N<sub>0</sub>&#039;</em> the number of samples of <em>x(t)</em>, by adding samples with a value of <em>0</em>. This addition of dummy samples is known as <strong>zero padding. </strong>zero padding increases the number of samples and it may help in getting a better idea of the spectrum <em>X(f)</em> from its samples <em>X<sub>r</sub></em>.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/index.php?sub=59&amp;brch=166&amp;sim=820&amp;cnt=1#link16"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><blink>Top<img alt="" src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/images/smiley/msn/thumbs_up.gif" align="absMiddle"></blink></big></span></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><a name="link12">&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Properties of discrete Fourier transform:</strong></big></span></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><big>The DFT is basically the Fourier transform of the sampled signal   which is repeated periodically. So the properties of the Fourier   transform can also applied for DFT.</big></p>
<p>&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>1.</strong></big></span> <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Linearity property:</strong></big></span> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<big>&nbsp; If &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=21c1097e7f7230d3fdf41932f0ea419c.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»§#8660;«/mo»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«/math»" align="middle"> and &nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=bb6ca5ca8bb52866af89e22fe6076f33.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»g«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»§#8660;«/mo»«msub»«mi»G«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«/math»" align="middle"> then<img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=748eb8472c17b6e9e07b49f596c5cfc9.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«mi»a«/mi»«mn»1«/mn»«mo».«/mo»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»+«/mo»«mi»a«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mo».«/mo»«msub»«mi»g«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»§#8660;«/mo»«mi»a«/mi»«mn»1«/mn»«mo».«/mo»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«mo»+«/mo»«mi»a«/mi»«mn»2«/mn»«mo».«/mo»«msub»«mi»G«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«/math»" align="middle"></big></p>
<p>&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>2.</strong></big></span> <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Time shifting (Circular shifting):</strong></big></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=aefe064dc2313f802b9f34a07e840abc.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mrow»«mi»k«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«/mrow»«/msub»«mo»§#8660;«/mo»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»j«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«msub»«mi»§#937;«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mi»n«/mi»«/mrow»«/msup»«/math»" align="middle"></big></p>
<p>&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><strong><big>3.</big></strong></span><strong> </strong><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Frequency shifting:</strong></big></span> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <big>&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=676ec7686c10e07699c8bd2e690ad35b.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«msup»«mi»e«/mi»«mrow»«mi»j«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«msub»«mi»§#937;«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mi»m«/mi»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«/mrow»«/msup»«mo»§#8660;«/mo»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mrow»«mi»r«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»m«/mi»«/mrow»«/msub»«/math»" align="middle"></big></p>
<p>&nbsp;<span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>4.</strong></big></span> <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><strong>Circular convolution:</strong></big></span> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<big> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=033b3f1ac6df2f392478538d6c305744.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»§#8855;«/mo»«msub»«mi»g«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»§#8660;«/mo»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«msub»«mi»G«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«/math»" align="middle"> &nbsp;&nbsp; and &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=317643019dee6dc052b1afb4693dd8ea.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«msub»«mi»g«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»§#8660;«/mo»«mfrac»«mn»1«/mn»«msub»«mi»N«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«/mfrac»«msub»«mi»X«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«mo»§#8855;«/mo»«msub»«mi»G«/mi»«mi»r«/mi»«/msub»«/math»" align="middle"></big></p>
<p>&nbsp;<big>For two &#039;<em>N<sub>0</sub></em>&#039; periodic sequences <em>x<sub>k</sub></em> and <em>&#039;g<sub>k</sub></em>&#039; the circular convolution is defined as</big></p>
<p><big>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/plugins/fckeditor_wiris/integration/showimage.php?formula=6c541329f8d24eb0a8c5c1035d7d51d7.png" title="Double click to edit" alt="«math xmlns=¨http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML¨»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»§#8855;«/mo»«msub»«mi»g«/mi»«mi»k«/mi»«/msub»«mo»=«/mo»«msub»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mn»0«/mn»«/mrow»«mrow»«msub»«mi»N«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mo»-«/mo»«mn»1«/mn»«/mrow»«/munderover»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»§nbsp;«/mo»«/mrow»«/msub»«msub»«mi»x«/mi»«mi»n«/mi»«/msub»«msub»«mi»g«/mi»«mrow»«mi»k«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«/mrow»«/msub»«munderover»«mo»§#8721;«/mo»«mrow»«mi»n«/mi»«mo»=«/mo»«mn»0«/mn»«/mrow»«mrow»«msub»«mi»N«/mi»«mn»0«/mn»«/msub»«mo»-«/mo»«mn»1«/mn»«/mrow»«/munderover»«msub»«mi»g«/mi»«mi»n«/mi»«/msub»«msub»«mi»f«/mi»«mrow»«mi»k«/mi»«mo»-«/mo»«mi»n«/mi»«/mrow»«/msub»«/math»" style="width: 267px; height: 65px;" align="middle"></big></p>
<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;   &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <a href="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/index.php?sub=59&amp;brch=166&amp;sim=820&amp;cnt=1#link15"><span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 255);"><big><blink>Top</blink></big></span><img src="http://iitg.vlab.co.in/fckeditor/editor/images/smiley/msn/thumbs_up.gif" alt="" align="absMiddle"></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p></div></div></td>
